reviews.review_text:
The Dark Dark Star
This is the end of the 14-show October tour [5 venues], and a night that stands out in what is, overall, a mediocre stretch. Though there is better material in the sets, the show has always been known for the freaky Dark Star; that used to circ as the Dark Dark Star. "Were you at Miami?" became a topic for the next few months on tour. "Dude, people just freaked out!". "They're really going dark now, man". They weren't really, but there was a transitional period between fall '89 and the spring '90 sound and setlists – one that started even before the sheets came off Dark Star. It appears that an AUD or SBD was not used as an accuracy guide for mixing down the OFF release, which plays like a newly-created album in places. First Set. To get Foolish Heart into shape, Jer really gives. It does work to warm them up, allowing for a brilliant Little Red Rooster, that they recognize and sit on for a while. Bobby gives more to Brent, rather than a full Bobby's Slide Practice™. Stagger Lee has good tempo, and Brent is great [his keys are more prominent on the SBD]. Jer wants another stab at Big River; takes a bonus solo. Brown-Eyed Women might be the year's best. It's detailed and Phil is a monster. Then, Victim is a big, arena-busting version. Check the crazy-abrupt 180 into Dough Knees. The drums here are especially good. [My opinion of the first set increased on re-listening, due to Stagger, Victim and DEMI]. Second Set. There's a brief Funiculì, Funiculà tuning [not on OFF], then a histrionic Estimated that's sort of spit out. With minor notes and some ominous synth, they are already building a darker tone. Brent goes all-in for Blow Away but it still doesn't gel (it would get better in Spring '90), with shoes-in-dryer and a hard stop. Given those set openers, it was opportune for Jer to fling out the four opening notes of Dark Star, the single song for which this show seems to be known. It's more free-form than usual, and they don't play through themes, making it as much Space as Star. Certain elements make it seem dark, or more intense, but there are Stars that seemed intense in '70, so let's call it most intense of the modern Stars. But most of it is not – it's even creaky until the last 10mins. It's no big deal at home, but imagine what it was like in the venue for the saucer-eyed with the light show and the volume the Dead used at the time. That sort of thing was so contagious, with some people wondering, "What's going on? Or is it just me?". But of course there's nothing going on. The Einstein–Rosen bridge that appears and allows sweetness and light just accommodates other shades, right? It's a law from the universe. We humans can tap the energy, but to the universe we're an unimportant blip, so why claim we're the energy masters? Isn't that hubris? Or, earthbound, perhaps it would not have seemed so dark if it had been better-played; you can almost hear band frustration in places. Conversely, you can also hear the boys smirking, "yup, this is where it's going, so just strap in". And where they went we went by default. Faustian? Sometimes. All part of the bus. Does it compare to 10/9/89, 3/29/90, 7/12/90 or 9/20/90? Parts are nice, but at 26mins there are long stretches that are meh. Then, the segue-in and Drums are hot (how often did you hear Mickey charge the crowd loud enough to be heard on the SBD?). With Space compelling hundreds to leave the venue (after 45mins of free-form playing), what's that tell you? They failed the test: no graduation certificate! Overall, of the four return Stars in '89 it's fourth best, but still a Must Hear Once. Some live elements heard in person [and SBD] are missing from the OFF mixdown [particularly the last 5mins], either by choice or because they were not on lines sent to the multi-track machines. This makes it less intense. There are also some new echoes and reverb added to the OFF [the last 2mins of DS and first 2mins of Drums are a new performance compared to AUD/SBD, which match throughout the set]. The fine Space also has a different mix on the OFF. The back nine is all solid. The Wheel is a long time coming, but worth the build up. In Watchtower Bobby slurs the verses like he's eating lunch at work. Jer almost always did justice to it in the late Brent era, but it's Bobby that adds the more-than-usual in the last minute, with a dueling weave. It's Brent that stipulates Stella stands stalwart. Unusually for an OFF, it has the complete NFA chant – including Jer returning and playing off the Heads. This tuning briefly includes GDtRFB, Mary Had a a Little Lamb, and a Country Gardens (and a quick Addams Family from Brent) 1st Set:  B+ 2nd Set: C+ Overall = 3¾ stars Highlights: Little Red Rooster – knowing it's good they dig in Brown-Eyed Women – maybe year's best & check Phil Don't Ease Me In – unexpected arrival, drums especially good SOURCES: The whole show is on 30 Trips, but 147766_UltraMatrix (the upgraded SBD) is not centered in the image like the OFF and has slightly better freqs for a bit warmer, rounder, more natural sound. The OFF has the clarity of multi-tracks but also a changed mix. There are two Tobin matrices, from different source material. The 147752_mtx is more balanced. Part of Space is on Infrared Roses. Blow Away is on Definitive Live.

Estimated>Blow>Star This is some of the best PRIME dead. Best  sound quality, best playing, I mean an Estimated>Blow>Star??!! EPIC Love Phil’s midi effects on Dark Star. So much of this just screams PRIME Dead. If you can’t realize that, you have my deepest sympathy. Thank you for the recording. 🙏
